In Java, a Stack is a linear data structure that follows the Last In First Out (LIFO) principle and is defined in the java.util package. Internally, it extends the Vector class.
a. Stack class maintains insertion order and allows duplicates and null values.
b. Grows dynamically when its capacity is exceeded.
c. All the methods of Stack are synchronized.
d. It is thread-safe.
e. Stack class implements List, RandomAccess, Cloneable, and Serializable interfaces.
The Stack class is a legacy class from early versions of Java. For new code, it is generally recommended to use ArrayDeque or LinkedList to implement stack behavior, as they offer better performance and flexibility in single-threaded scenarios.

import java.util.Stack;
​
public class Geeks {
    public static void main(String[] args)
    {
        // Create a new stack
        Stack<Integer> s = new Stack<>();
​
        // Push elements onto the stack
        s.push(1);
        s.push(2);
        s.push(3);
        s.push(4);
​
        // Pop elements from the stack
        while (!s.isEmpty()) {
            System.out.println(s.pop());
        }
    }
}

Output
4
3
2
1
Explanation:

a. Elements are added to the stack using the push() method, placing each item on top.
b. A loop runs while the stack is not empty, checked using the empty() method.
c. Elements are removed and printed using the pop() method in LIFO order.

